<DocLayout title="Funding & Support" description="How the AEGIS Initiative is funded and how your organization can support governance-first AI security.">
  <h1>Funding &amp; Support</h1>

  <section>
    <h2>Current Funding</h2>
    <p>
      The AEGIS Initiative is <strong>privately funded by its founder,
      Kenneth Tannenbaum</strong>, through Finnoybu IP LLC. All infrastructure,
      research, publication, standards engagement, and development costs are
      borne entirely by the organization's sole principal.
    </p>
    <p>
      There are no external investors, corporate sponsors, or grant funding at
      this time. This independence ensures that AEGIS governance positions are
      driven by technical merit and public interest — not by the priorities of
      funders.
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <section>
    <h2>Why We Need Support</h2>
    <p>
      Building enforceable governance for AI is not a weekend project. The AEGIS
      Initiative maintains 11 repositories, publishes peer-reviewed research,
      engages with federal standards bodies, and develops runtime enforcement
      tools — all on a single person's resources.
    </p>
    <p>
      To continue and expand this work, we need sustainable funding. Specifically:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Infrastructure</strong> — hosting, CI/CD, domain management, and tooling for the ecosystem</li>
      <li><strong>Research &amp; publication</strong> — conference fees, DOI minting, peer review processes</li>
      <li><strong>Standards engagement</strong> — travel, participation fees, and formal submissions to NIST, IEEE, and NCCoE</li>
      <li><strong>Team growth</strong> — bringing on domain experts in AI safety, policy, and systems engineering</li>
      <li><strong>Legal &amp; compliance</strong> — trademark protection, licensing, and eventual non-profit formation</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <section>
    <h2>How to Support AEGIS</h2>

    <h3>Sponsorship</h3>
    <p>
      Corporate and organizational sponsors help sustain the initiative's
      infrastructure and research output. Sponsorship is acknowledged publicly
      and does not grant editorial influence over governance positions or
      technical decisions.
    </p>

    <h3>Partnerships</h3>
    <p>
      We welcome partnerships with organizations working on AI safety, governance,
      and responsible deployment. Partnership can take many forms — joint research,
      shared infrastructure, co-authored publications, or pilot implementations of
      AEGIS governance in production systems.
    </p>

    <h3>Grants &amp; Institutional Funding</h3>
    <p>
      The AEGIS Initiative is exploring formal non-profit status to enable
      grant applications and institutional funding. If your organization funds
      AI safety, governance, or open-source security work, we'd like to discuss
      alignment.
    </p>

    <h3>Individual Contributions</h3>
    <p>
      If you believe in governance-first AI security, you can contribute by
      engaging with our open-source repositories, citing our publications, or
      spreading the word. We are also exploring mechanisms for direct financial
      contributions as part of our non-profit formation.
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <section>
    <h2>Get in Touch</h2>
    <p>
      If your organization is interested in sponsoring, partnering with, or
      funding the AEGIS Initiative, please contact us:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>General inquiries:</strong> <a href="mailto:contact@aegis-initiative.com">contact@aegis-initiative.com</a></li>
      <li><strong>Partnerships &amp; sponsorship:</strong> <a href="mailto:partners@aegis-initiative.com">partners@aegis-initiative.com</a></li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      We respond to every inquiry. Independence from funders is a feature, not a
      limitation — but sustainability requires support. We're looking for partners
      who share the conviction that AI governance is too important to be optional.
    </p>
  </section>
</DocLayout>
